🏗️ Preface — Objectives & Content

The Preface is your first opportunity to connect, orient, and build trust. It sets the tone, frames the purpose, and helps readers understand why this isn’t just another methodology manual but a lived guide. In complex enterprise delivery, that human framing makes the difference.

Here’s what the Preface should include, how the wisdom layer shows up, and a sample outline.

⸻

📋 What the Preface Must Contain

| Element                                   | Purpose                                                                 | Wisdom / Coaching Layer                                                                                   |
|--------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Why I wrote this manual / My delivery scars| Establishes credibility and vulnerability                               | VP Reflection — an anecdote of a failed or painful program decision                                       |
| What this manual is (and isn’t)            | Set boundaries and expectations                                         | Why This Matters — to prevent misuse or disillusionment                                                   |
| Intended Audience & How to Use It          | Let people self-assess fit (Delivery Managers, QA Leads, Architects)    | Pro Tip — suggested reading paths or ways to consume (chapter by chapter, parts you can skip)             |
| Terminology and Conventions                | Explain “Delivery Team / Customer Team,” annotation styles, callouts    | Caution / Guidance Box — “Don’t skip this. Many misunderstand contracts / roles because they ignored this page.” |
| How to Read This Manual                    | Advice on how to traverse, what to skip, how to jump across sections    | From the Field — how readers should treat it in practice (keep it as a living reference, not a locked document) |
| Acknowledgments / Context                  | Optionally, credit reviewers or context; use sparingly                  | Light, minimal                                                                                            |
| Date / Versioning Note                     | So readers know this is versioned and may evolve                        | Small note, no callout                                                                                    |


⸻

🧠 Where Wisdom Layer Appears in the Preface
	•	Right in the first “Why I wrote this” section, insert a VP Reflection: a story of one of the hardest escalations you handled, and how process (or lack thereof) changed your view.
	•	In “What this manual is (and isn’t)”, include a Why This Matters callout: emphasize that this manual is not a rigid law but a structured lens for judgment.
	•	In “How to Use It,” add a Pro Tip about customizing the rituals to your project’s context — don’t force a 20-step meeting in a 6-person program.
	•	In “Terminology & Conventions,” include a Caution about ignoring the language rules (mixing “vendor”/“client” will generate confusion) or skipping the reader’s orientation.
	•	In “How to Read,” a From the Field note: “I returned to certain sections dozens of times across programs — this manual is not linear; it’s a map.”

